    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, that's frustrating! A red light that persists after a standard reboot usually means the router isn't getting a signal from the modem or the ISP's network is down, but before you call them, you can try a \"hard reset\" or \"factory reset\" on the router itself. This involves holding down the small reset button on the back of the device for about 10-15 seconds until all the lights flash, which wipes all your custom settings and restores the router to its original state. However, be warned that this will erase your Wi-Fi password and any port forwarding rules, so you'll need to reconfigure everything afterward. If you're not comfortable doing that, you could also try checking if the modem's light is green or amber; if the modem light is red, the issue is likely with the ISP's network, not your router. In that case, calling your ISP is the best next step, but if you're feeling adventurous, you could try replacing the Ethernet cable between the modem and router to rule out a faulty connection. Just remember, if you're not sure what you're doing, it's better to ask a friend or family member for help, as messing with the wrong settings could cause more problems",
